 The brain is an energy-hungry organ. It consumes approximately one fifth of the total body’s blood flow and has a huge number of neurons that consume vast quantities of glucose.
All this leads to tremendous demands on our own personal supplies – which can easily become depleted by long-term high-level activities such as work, sleep deprivation or simply being active during periods when you are not awake (such as sleeping).
It also means we have more than just one set of cells in each area of our brains;
